    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3546237807" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3546237807" />
    <a title="Fred Svoboda" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/33093229-fred-svoboda"><img alt="Fred Svoboda" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1405458489p2/33093229.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3546237807?book_show_action=true">Sep 13, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fred Svoboda" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fred Svoboda" href="/user/show/33093229-fred-svoboda">Fred Svoboda</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3546237807" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6936944757744216986">This is in Dick Francis&apos;s Wacko Dysfunctional Extended Family subgenre, and regrettably it leads to Wacko Dysfunctional mystery novel. Our protagonist and his father are rather nice guys (and Dad is hugely rich, already having settled juicy trust funds on his nine children by five ex wives). However, Greed (or Need) is the family downfall, and someone is trying to knock off Dad in hopes of shaking loose an inheritance that will make life into easy street. <br/><br/>Protagonist insists that dad split the w</span>
  <span id="freeText6936944757744216986" style="display:none">This is in Dick Francis's Wacko Dysfunctional Extended Family subgenre, and regrettably it leads to Wacko Dysfunctional mystery novel. Our protagonist and his father are rather nice guys (and Dad is hugely rich, already having settled juicy trust funds on his nine children by five ex wives). However, Greed (or Need) is the family downfall, and someone is trying to knock off Dad in hopes of shaking loose an inheritance that will make life into easy street. <br /><br />Protagonist insists that dad split the wealth evenly in the will, but everyone thinks protagonist actually is angling to take it all, despite the fact that he repeatedly points out he is the only one treating Dad well, which of course makes Dad trust him.<br /><br />Did I mention that most of these children are married, and many have their own children?<br /><br />Needless to say, keeping these all straight is a major undertaking despite a Francis-provided chart and summaries of each major character's character--or lack of same. I couldn't manage it, and I'll bet that many others had the same problem. <br /><br />Francis tries to suggest positive elements in many of these people, but he is not convincing me. Cut the number of characters in half, and it might be possible. Have Dad show everyone the will--which he refuses to do-- or give every child an anticipatory bequest of a million or so and there would be no reason for anyone to kill him.<br /><br />The above suggests how fragile the tissue of plot is.<br /><br />And I found that I didn't care for any of these people.<br /><br />Don't bother.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6936944757744216986" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


